Fine, fine, I'll give them this much: they appear to be helpful in the fight against catastrophic climate change. As explained by the National Wildlife Foundation's Robyn Carmichael, sea otters frequently eat sea urchins, which in turn are known for eating massive amounts of kelp, which is very good at taking in carbon dioxide during photosynthesis. More otters -> fewer sea urchins -> more kelp -> less global warming. One studyfound that kelp beds where sea otters are present soak up 12 times as much carbon dioxide as beds where they're not. The overall effect isn't that large, but every bit helps, and otters deserve some credit for chipping in.

Seals often slap their flippers against their bodies, a behavior known as âclappingâ or âflipperslapping.â This action serves multiple purposes for seals. It can be a form of communication, used to signal other seals or to express dominance or aggression. Sometimes, this behavior is also observed during play or as a means of catching the attention of nearby seals or humans. Some people say that success is not a destination, but a journey. They believe that the obstacles and challenges that we face along the way are what make us stronger and more resilient. But what if those obstacles are 1,806 not just metaphorical, but literal? What if they are not just problems or difficulties, but actual people who get in our way?

In this video, you will see a runner who is determined to win his race, no matter what. He is running very fast on a track, when suddenly a small kid jumps onto the track and blocks his path. Most people would stop, or slow down, or try to avoid the kid. But not this runner. He does not let anything stop him. He dashes the kid and carries on his race, leaving the kid behind in a cloud of dust.

Judging from our fashion, many might think Sponge Cake, Mocha and Donut are girls :). As we have recently made new friends on Instagram, we would like to reintroduce ourselves:

Sponge Cake (the orange/ginger one) is a total attention-seeker. He often approaches random ladies in Central park and asks for pets. 

Mocha (the cream one) is the calmest and most well-behaved kitty. He would never do anything to upset you, and allows people to hug him. 

Donut (the white one) often begs at the door to go outside. When he goes on adventures on his backpack, you can hear him sniffing the whole time. 

A question we often receive is how we make the cats get along. The key is to ensure they never have to compete for resources such as vertical spaces like cat trees or shelves, litter boxes, hiding spots and resting areas. 

Have a great Caturday!

In this second episode, I introduced the acupuncture point AnMian, a favorite point for insomnia(trouble sleeping). About 1 in 10 people have at least a moderate level of insomnia. A commonly used point to treat insomnia is âAnmianâ, which translates into âPeaceful Sleepâ. 

In Chinese Medicine, when you are unable to sleep, it is considered that your âspirit is not housed properlyâ and this acupuncture point can help to settle it again by âcalming the spiritâ. You can use pressure on this point to create this effect. 

To find it, run your finger back half an inch from behind your earlobe (youâll feel a small depression), and massage gently in small circles. Do this for 1-3 minutes. You can do it yourself or do it for someone else. You should have a deep aching feeling and a feeling of relaxation. Let me know if it works tomorrowð¥°
